SIMPLE: falsification
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Falsification
<hw>Fal`si*fi*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>falsification</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of falsifying,
or making false; a counterfeiting; the giving to a thing an appearance
of something which it is not.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To counterfeit the living image of king in his person exceedeth
all <qex>falsifications</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Willful misstatement or misrepresentation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Extreme necessity . . . forced him upon this bold and violent
<qex>falsification</qex> of the doctrine of the alliance.</q>
<rj><qau>Bp. Warburton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Equity)</fld> <def>The showing an item of charge in
an account to be wrong.</def> <rj><au>Story.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Falsificator</ent>⟦br⟧
